title: iNaturalist Data
text:
Here is what that area looks like plotted on a flat map.

suppressMessages(library(magrittr))

Warning: package 'magrittr' was built under R version 4.0.5

library(ggplot2)
nskml <- sf::read_sf("NineSpringsArea.kml") %>% dplyr::select(-Description)
nsc <- sf::read_sf("NineSpringsCreek.kml") %>% dplyr::select(-Description)
bbt <- sf::read_sf("BaxterBikeTrail.kml") %>% dplyr::select(-Description)
streets <- sf::read_sf("Streets.kml") %>% dplyr::select(-Description)

ggplot() + geom_sf(data = nskml, color = "orange", size = 2) +
  geom_sf(data = nsc, color = "blue", size = 1) +
  geom_sf(data = bbt, color = "red", size = 1) +
  geom_sf(data = streets, color = "yellow", size = 0.75)

title: BriarPatch Youth Services
text: In Dane County it is estimated approximately 300 youth go to bed homeless each night. 1 in 3 youth will be approached for sex in exchange for food, shelter, drugs, etc. within 48 hours of leaving home; 75% of these youth have already or will drop out of school. These are good kids in bad situations and they need our help. The staff at Briarpatch Youth Services work with these youth to make sure they have the resources and support they need in order to succeed.

title: Friends of Capital Springs
text:
The Friends work to connect the entire community with the wonders of nature found at Capital Springs Recreation Area, including miles of undisturbed lakeshore, large stretches of oak savanna and prairie, meandering Nine Springs Creek, mixed oak woodlands and many, many acres of wetlands.
This 2,500-acre, urban-edge park is centrally located in Dane County, extending from Fish Hatchery Road to the western shore of Lake Waubesa.

title: Madison Area Food Pantry Gardens
text: The Madison Area Food Pantry Gardens, Inc. is established to provide fresh vegetables for use by area food pantries and meal programs. The work of planning, planting, harvesting, garden maintenance, and delivery of produce is primarily done by volunteers. Land used for garden sites is rented from or given for use by generous landowners. Madison Area Food Pantry Garden volunteers also glean produce from various local growers who agree to donate their excess crops to area food pantries.
